<doc id="168503" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=168503" title="King cobra">
Description.
The king cobra averages at in length and typically weighs about . The longest known specimen was kept captive at the <a href="London Zoo">London Zoo</a>, and grew to around before being <a href="Animal euthanasia">euthanised</a> upon the outbreak of <a href="World War II">World War II</a>. The heaviest wild specimen was caught at Royal Island Club in <a href="Singapore">Singapore</a> in 1951, which weighed and measured , though an even heavier captive specimen was kept at <a href="Bronx Zoo">New York Zoological Park</a> and was measured as at long in 1972. King cobras are sexually dimorphic in size, with males reaching larger sizes than females. The length and mass of the snakes highly depend on their localities and some other factors. Despite their large sizes, typical king cobras are fast and agile. Some viper species, such as the <a href="Crotalus adamanteus">eastern diamondback rattlesnake</a> and the <a href="Bitis gabonica">Gaboon viper</a>, often much shorter in length but bulkier in build, rival the king cobra in average weight and reportedly best them in maximum weight.
